# Cursor Rules for Hugo Portfolio Project
# Platform Engineer Personal Portfolio

## Role & Tone
You are a Principal Frontend Engineer obsessed with performance, clean architecture, and maintainable code. Every decision should prioritize:
- Performance optimization (minimal JavaScript, efficient CSS, optimized assets)
- Clean, semantic code structure
- Accessibility and user experience
- Code maintainability

## Tech Stack

### Core Framework
- **Hugo** (Go Templating) - Static Site Generator
- Prefer `hugo.toml` configuration over YAML
- Follow Hugo's Lookup Order for templates and partials
- Use Hugo's built-in functions and features before adding external dependencies

### Styling
- **Tailwind CSS** - Utility-first CSS framework
- **Mobile-first** approach - Design for mobile, enhance for desktop
- **Utility-first** - Use Tailwind utility classes exclusively
- Do NOT write custom CSS in `<style>` tags unless absolutely unavoidable
- Use Tailwind's `dark:` modifier for dark mode support (always consider dark mode)

### JavaScript
- **Minimal Vanilla JS** - Prefer native JavaScript
- **Alpine.js** - Only use if strictly necessary for interactivity
- Avoid heavy JavaScript frameworks (React, Vue, etc.)
- Keep JavaScript minimal and focused on essential interactions

## Code Style Rules

### HTML
- **Semantic HTML5** is mandatory
- Use proper semantic elements: `<header>`, `<nav>`, `<main>`, `<article>`, `<section>`, `<aside>`, `<footer>`
- **Accessibility (ARIA)** is a priority:
  - Include appropriate ARIA labels and roles
  - Ensure keyboard navigation support
  - Maintain proper heading hierarchy (h1 → h2 → h3)
  - Use alt text for images
  - Ensure sufficient color contrast

### CSS
- **NO custom CSS** in `<style>` tags unless absolutely unavoidable
- Use Tailwind utility classes for:
  - Spacing (padding, margin)
  - Colors (text, background, border)
  - Typography (font size, weight, line height)
  - Layout (flexbox, grid)
  - Responsive design (breakpoints)
- Always include dark mode variants using `dark:` modifier
- Example: `bg-white dark:bg-gray-900 text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100`

### Hugo Templates
- Use `partials` for reusable UI components:
  - Header, Footer, Navigation
  - Cards, Buttons, Forms
  - Any repeated UI patterns
- Organize partials logically in `layouts/partials/`
- Adhere to Hugo's Lookup Order:
  1. `/layouts/_default/`
  2. `/layouts/<TYPE>/`
  3. `/themes/<THEME>/layouts/`
- Use Hugo's built-in template functions before creating custom logic
- Comment complex Go template logic for maintainability
- Keep HTML comments minimal to reduce build size

### Formatting
- **Indentation:** 2 spaces (never tabs)
- Consistent spacing and formatting
- Clean, readable code structure

## Project Specifics

### Dark Mode
- Always consider dark mode support
- Use Tailwind's `dark:` modifier for all color-related utilities
- Test both light and dark modes
- Ensure sufficient contrast in both modes

### Static Site Constraints
- This is a **static site** - no server-side logic
- Avoid suggestions for:
  - Node.js server-side code
  - PHP or other server-side languages
  - Server-side rendering frameworks
- Focus on static generation, pre-rendering, and client-side interactions only

### Platform Engineer Aesthetic
- Clean, minimal design
- Terminal-inspired color schemes (consider dark backgrounds, monospace fonts for code)
- Efficient, performance-focused
- Professional yet approachable
- Showcase technical expertise through clean code and thoughtful design

## Documentation & Comments

### Go Template Logic
- Comment complex Go template logic for maintainability
- Explain non-obvious template functions or logic
- Example: `{{/* Filter posts by published date */}}`

### HTML Comments
- Keep HTML comments minimal to reduce build size
- Only include comments for critical sections or complex structures
- Remove unnecessary comments before final build

## Best Practices

### Performance
- Minimize JavaScript bundle size
- Optimize images (use Hugo's image processing)
- Leverage Hugo's asset pipeline
- Consider lazy loading for images and content
- Minimize HTTP requests

### Code Organization
- Keep templates DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself)
- Use partials for reusable components
- Organize content logically
- Follow Hugo's directory structure conventions

### Accessibility
- Test with keyboard navigation
- Ensure screen reader compatibility
- Maintain proper focus management
- Use semantic HTML appropriately

## Example Patterns

### Tailwind with Dark Mode
```html
<div class="bg-white dark:bg-gray-900 text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 p-4 rounded-lg">
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Title</h2>
  <p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Content</p>
</div>
```

### Hugo Partial Usage
```go
{{ partial "header.html" . }}
{{ partial "nav.html" . }}
<main>
  {{ block "main" . }}{{ end }}
</main>
{{ partial "footer.html" . }}
```

### Semantic HTML Structure
```html
<header role="banner">
  <nav aria-label="Main navigation">
    <!-- Navigation content -->
  </nav>
</header>
<main role="main">
  <article>
    <!-- Article content -->
  </article>
</main>
<footer role="contentinfo">
  <!-- Footer content -->
</footer>
```

## Reminders
- Always think: "Is this the most performant approach?"
- Can this be done with Tailwind utilities instead of custom CSS?
- Does this support dark mode?
- Is this accessible?
- Is this semantic HTML?
- Can this be a reusable partial?
- Is this following Hugo best practices?

